THE STUDENT PILOT EXPERIENCED A POWER LOSS ON TAKEOFF AT 500 FEET AND 
MADE A FORCED LANDING IN A GRAVEL PIT. THE ENGINE WAS TEST RUN 
SATISFACTORILY AFTER THE ACCIDENT. THE CLOSEST RECORDED WEATHER WAS 25 
MILES AWAY AND HAD A TEMPERATURE OF 28 DEGREES F AND A DEWPOINT OF 16 
DEGREES F. HOWEVER THE FAA REPORTED THE DEWPOINT WAS NOT 
REPRESENTATIVE OF THE AIRPORT WHICH IS TYPICALLY MORE HUMID DUE TO THE 
CLOSE PROXIMITY OF PONDS AND STREAMS. 
THE PILOT'S IMPROPER USE OF CARBURETOR HEAT WHICH CAUSED A POWER LOSS 
AND A FORCED LANDING IN UNSUITABLE TERRAIN. FACTORS RELATED TO THE 
ACCIDENT WERE CARBURETOR ICING CONDITIONS AND THE PILOTS LACK OF TOTAL 
EXPERIENCE. 
